text: Elucidating the Sugar Tailoring Steps in the Cytorhodin Biosynthetic Pathway †,‡ Chun Gui, † CAS Key Laboratory of Tropical Marine Bio-resources and Ecology, Guangdong Key Laboratory of Marine Materia Medica, RNAM Center for Marine Microbiology, South China Sea Institute of Oceanology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, 164 West Xingang Road, Guangzhou 510301, China ‡ University of Chinese Academy of Sciences, 19 Yuquan Road, Beijing, 110039, China § Shandong Key Laboratory of Applied Mycology, School of Life Sciences, Qingdao Agricultural University, Qingdao, 266109, China ⊥ Syngenta Jealott’s Hill International Research Centre, Bracknell, Berkshire RG42 6EY, U.K. *S Supporting Information A nthracyclines represent a large family of type II polyketide- derived metabolites with diverse bioactivities.1 Especially characteristic of the anthracyclines is their cytotoxicity as is reﬂected by the success of the clinically employed drugs daunorubicin, doxorubicin, epirubicin, idarubicin, and aclacino- mycin (Supporting Information (SI), Figure S1). Notably, minor modiﬁcations of the pendant glycosyl moieties often alter anthracycline cytotoxicity.2 Cytorhodins X (1) and Y (2) (Figure 1A) consist of a linear tetracyclic polyketide backbone and feature a 7-dexoy-aglycone; 1 and 2 were originally isolated from Streptomyces sp. HPLY-11472 (DSM 2658) and DSM 11149, respectively.3,4 Both agents project a C-10 linked trisaccharide and a rhodosamine sugar moiety at the C-9 of γ-rhodomycinone. This glycosylation pattern is rare among the anthracyclines. Additionally, 1 is cytotoxic to L1210 murine leukemia cells and 2 exhibits cytotoxic activity against HT29 and LXFL 529L cells with IC50 values of <0.3 μg/mL.3,4

To date, the biosynthetic machinery driving 1 and 2 assembly has evaded study. Especially unclear has been the system of glycosyltransferases (GTs) responsible for generating the unique glycosylation pattern seen in 1 and 2. Here we report: (i) puriﬁcation and elucidation of ﬁve cytorhodin analogues from a dehydratase (DH) site-directed mutagenesis mutant Streptomy- ces sp. SCSIO 1666/ΔtrdA1DH along with identiﬁcation of the cyt biosynthetic gene cluster (BGC), and (ii) in vivo inactivation of three GT encoding genes cytG1−G3 and two auxiliary P450-like protein encoding genes cytL and cytW which aﬀorded nine derivatives 6−14 (Figure 1B) enabling us to propose GT- mediated tailoring steps involved in cytorhodin biosynthesis. ABSTRACT: Anthracycline antitumor cytorhodins X and Y feature a rare 9α-glycoside and 7-dexoy-aglycone. Character- ization of the cytorhodin gene cluster from Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666 through gene inactivations and metabolite analyses reveals three glycosyltransferases (GTs) involved in the sugar tailoring steps. The duo of CytG1 and CytL eﬀects C-7 glycosylation with L-rhodosamine whereas the iterative GT CytG3 and CytW similarly modiﬁes both C-9 and C-10 positions. CytG2 also acts iteratively by incorporating the second and third sugar moiety into the trisaccharide chains at the C-7 or C-10 position. © XXXX American Chemical Society

Inactivation of a site-directed mutagenesis strain Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666/ΔtrdA1DH, from Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666 in which the conserved DH domain motif in trdA1 from the tirandamycin BGC was point mutated (SI, Figure S2), resulted in the abolishment of tirandamycins which otherwise diverted the metabolic ﬂux to the type II PKS pathway (Figure 2, ii). A series of new peaks with UV absorptions characteristic of daunorubicin in the extract of strain Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666/ΔtrdA1DH were observed. Accordingly, large scale fermentation of the Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666/ΔtrdA1DH mutant strain enabled the isolation and elucidation of ﬁve anthracycline compounds, namely cytorhodins X (1)3 and Y (2),4 cosmomycins A (3) and B (4),6−8 and iremycin (5) (Figure 1A).9 All of these compounds were elucidated by HRESIMS, 1H, and 13C NMR spectroscopic methods and comparisons with previously reported literatures. Based on the chemical structures of cytorhodins, cosmomycins A and B, and iremycin, we hypothesize that they are assembled by the same BGC and that the ultimate products of the assembly line are 1 and 2. Among these putative BGCs, candidate most likely responsible for cytorhodin biosynthesis is cluster 25, a type II PKS. This gene cluster contains 51 open reading frames (ORFs) (Figure 3A) and spans about 58 kb of contiguous genomic DNA. The nucleotide sequences have been deposited in the GenBank with accession number MF773975. It shows 97% identity to the cosmomycin D BGC,10,11 and its deduced gene products show high similarity to proteins identiﬁed in other anthracycline BGCs (SI, Table S4). To further validate our hypothesis, cyt2, encoding a ketosynthase (KS) within cluster 25, was disrupted by λ-RED recombination technology.12,13 The resultant double crossover mutant strain was identiﬁed and conﬁrmed on the basis of its kanamycin sensitive and apramycin resistant phenotype; its genotype was further validated by PCR (SI, Figure S3). The obtained mutant strain was fermented, and the extract of the broth was analyzed by HPLC. The mutant strain completely failed to produce 1−5 (Figure 2, iii) thereby demonstrating the indispensable role of this gene cluster in cytorhodin biosynthesis.

Biosynthetically, cytorhodins are typical type II PKS derived metabolites initiated by a minimal polyketide synthase composed of β-ketoacyl synthase alpha (KSα) Cyt1, β-ketoacyl synthase beta (KSβ) Cyt2, and an acyl carrier protein (ACP) CytE, which starts with a propionyl-CoA. The starter unit is subsequently extended by nine malonyl-CoA units to form the C-21 backbone which then gets processed by the ketoreductase, aromatases, and cyclases to form the correct folding patterns (SI, Figure S9).

The glycosylation patterns in cytorhodins X and Y diﬀer from other identiﬁed anthracyclines inspiring signiﬁcant interest and excitement from our group. It is noteworthy that the three identiﬁed GTs, CytG1, CytG2, and CytG3 within the cyt cluster show high identity to three GTs identiﬁed in the cosmomycin D BGC (SI, Table S4). In a fashion similar to that of the cosmomycin D BGC, two genes, cytL and cytW encoding for P450-like proteins, were observed directly downstream of cytG1 and cytG3. To verify the function of GTs and the putative auxiliary proteins in cytorhodin biosynthesis, we individually inactivated cytG1, cytG2, cytG3, cytL, and cytW in Streptomyces sp. SCSIO1666/ΔtrdA1DH and obtained corresponding double crossover mutant strains (SI, Figures S4−S8). HPLC analyses of broth extracts from fermentations of the mutants (Figure 2) revealed a discrepancy of metabolite proﬁles between the GT mutant strains and the wild type strain. Notably, similar metabolite proﬁles of ΔcytL and ΔcytG1, and almost identical metabolite proﬁles of ΔcytW and ΔcytG3, were observed. This observation indicated that the P450-like proteins CytL and CytW likely play chaperone-like roles in glycosyl transfer chemistry similar to their homologues DesVIII14 involved in pikromycin biosynthesis and AknT15 in the aclacinomycin pathway, respectively. Large scale fermentation of these mutant strains led to isolation and elucidation of intermediates 6, 7, and 14 (from ΔcytG1 mutant strain), 7−9, and 10 (from ΔcytG2 mutant strain), and 7, and 11−13 (from ΔcytG3 mutant strain) (Figure 1). Similar to doxorubicin and rhodomycin D,20 the anthracycline precursor of cytorhodin Y is proposed to be 6. As expected, compound 6 was isolated as a major constituent from the ΔcytG1 mutant strain. Besides intermediate 6, compounds 1−5, 7, and 14 were also isolated from the ΔcytG1 mutant strain. This indicates that CytG1 has no involvement with glycosylation at either the C-9 or C-10 position. RhoG (92% identity) from the rhodomycin pathway,21 and to AknS (46% identity)22 from the aclacinomycin biosynthetic pathway, respectively. That these putative homologues can transfer the ﬁrst L-rhodosamine moiety to aglycones at C-7 was readily validated. Accordingly, we posit that CytG1 may also function as L-rhodosamine transferase. The ability of CytG1 to directly append L-rhodosamine to the C-7 position of 6 is consistent with the identiﬁcation of intermediate 8 from the ΔcytG2 mutant strain. As anticipated, disruption of CytL resulted in a similar HPLC metabolite proﬁle compared to that of the ΔcytG1 mutant strain indicating its auxiliary protein role in cytorhodin biosynthesis. Generally, the catalytic decarboxylation at C-10 was noted only after glycosylation, as conﬁrmed by the use of the RdmC and RdmB pair in the rhodomycin producer S. purpurascens.23 We propose that homologous proteins CytI (92% identity to RdmC) and CytH (84% identity to RdmB) encoded within the cytorhodin cluster eﬀect decarboxylation en route to the cytorhodins.

Compounds 5 and 7−10 were isolated from the ΔcytG2 mutant. The isolation of new compound 9 as a minor component containing 2-deoxy-L-fucose at C-7 reveals the substrate ﬂexibility of CytG1. This ﬂexibility is similar to that seen for the CytG1 putative homologue AknS, which converges ε- rhodomycinone and 2-deoxy-L-fucose to generate 2-deoxyfuco- syl-rhodomycinone.17 Compounds 5, 8, and 9 each possess one sugar (rhodosamine for 5 and 8, 2-deoxy-L-fucose for 9) attached via C-10 or C-7, respectively, indicating that CytG2 is responsible for appending the second deoxysugar 2-deoxy-L-fucose (or L- rhodinose) onto these intermediates. CytG2 shows similarity to CosK (95% identity) from the cosmomycin D pathway10 and to AknK (65% identity)22 from the aclacinomycin biosynthetic pathway, respectively. The putative AknK can transfer 2-deoxy-L- fucose in two sequential reactions to yield a trisaccharide product attached at the C-7 position in vitro. Similarly, CosK may also function as an iterative GT to incorporate two sugar moieties into

the trisacharide chain at both C-7 and C-10 positions. Termination of CytG2 function thus stops the production of 11−13 and cosmomycin A and B (Figure 1). It stands to reason that CytG2 is responsible for generating the disaccharide compound 11 from 8, and then generating the trisaccharide compounds 12 and 13 from 11. Additionally, CytG2 also sequentially transfers two sugar moieties onto 5 to form cosmomycin A and B. Thus, CytG2 represents an iterative GT to form the trisacharide chain at both C-7 and C-10 positions. Compounds 7 and 11−13 isolated from the ΔcytG3 mutant lack moieties at the C-10 and C-9 positions. Notably, compound 7 features a 7-dexoy-aglycone and was the major constituent in these fermentations. By comparison to 3−5 isolated from the wild type strain, it is rational to postulate that 7 serves as the biosynthetic precursor to iremycin (5) by virtue of its direct glycosylation with L-rhodosamine. The identical metabolite proﬁle of the ΔcytW mutant strain compared to that of the ΔcytG3 mutant strain also indicates its auxiliary protein role in cytorhodin biosynthesis. This rationale also invokes the importance of the CytG3 and CytW pair in C-10 rhodosamine transfer during cytorhodin biosynthesis. This tailoring enzyme pair appears to drive the initial glycosylation step en route to the cosmomycins and cytorhodins; without linkage, CytG1 and CytG2 chemistries cannot proceed in these pathways. Informed by the substitution patterns seen in 3−5, it is clear that C-9 sugar tethering is the ultimate glycosylation step en route to 1 and 2. these ﬁndings we propose a series of glycosylation steps in the cytorhodin X/Y pathway (Figure 3B) in which ε-rhodomycinone (6) plays a pivotal role. On one hand, the CytG1 and CytL pair can catalyze the tethering of L- rhodosamine or 2-deoxy-L-fucose to the C-7 position of 6; the resulting glycosylated adducts decarboxymethylation of renders 8 and 9. CytG2-mediated glycosylation of 8 with 2- deoxy-L-fucose aﬀords 11; subsequent iterative glycosylation of 11 with 2-deoxy-L-fucose aﬀords trisaccharide 12. In addition, glycosylation of 11 with rhodinose aﬀords 13. Alternatively, 6 may suﬀer both C-10 decarboxymethylation and C-7 reduction to aﬀord 7. The iterative CytG3 and CytW enzyme pair then appends L-rhodosamine to 7 at C-10 and, after completion of the C-10 linked trisaccharide (by CytG2), to the C-9 OH moiety. In summary, we have identiﬁed and characterized the cyt gene cluster from Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666. Elucidating the glycosylation steps in cytorhodin biosynthesis reveals two iterative GTs, namely CytG2 and CytG3. CytG2 shows substrate ﬂexibility to attach the second and third sugar to the trisaccharide chains at both C-7 and C-10 positions. CytG3 is an iterative GT that attaches L-rhodosamine at both the C-9 and C-10 moieties in anthracycline family compounds. Two P450-like proteins CytL and CytW are proposed to act as auxiliary proteins during the glycosyl transfer process. The GT identiﬁed from the cytorhodin BGC provides an opportunity to generate new anthracycline derivatives for structure−activity relationship studies by combinatorial biosynthesis.
